                <lb n="2"/> בן מ<gap reason="illegible" quantity="3"/> <gap reason="illegible" quantity="2"/> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"
                    unit="character"/>
                <lb n="3"/>שלם <space quantity="1" unit="character"/> נפש <unclear>מ</unclear>
                <lb n="4"/>ושלש שנה <unclear>ש</unclear><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"
                    unit="character"/>
                <lb n="5"/><gap reason="illegible" quantity="5"/> יש </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Son of M… whole… tombstone… And three year(s)</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text records an epitaph of an unknown person, possibly male (based on the
                    masculine word בן on the second line). This might be the beginning of a
                    filiation, as appears in other tombstones.</p>
                <p>line 3: The word נפש can be translated either as “soul” or as “tombstone” - both meanings can be found on other Jewish tombstones.</p>
                <p>line 4: The number ושלש might be a record of the deceased’s age at death, which would make him at least 23 years
                    old. Alternatively it may be part of the date of his death as is common in other
                    Jewish tombstones.</p></div>
            

